@jot @rosiesherry "Measure" is somewhat of a loaded term. The real key is basically observation. Act -> observe -> course correct -> repeat. Measuring is a subset of observation, and often a great tool esp. when dealing with large or unintuitive numbers. But there are other ways to observe, too.

text:
This is awkward. The latest guest on the IH podcast is… me!

@gilbert and @djrosent from @AcquiredFM interviewed me about:
 
- going through YC + my 6 failed startups
- how I built IH
- being acquired by @stripe
- a future with millions of indie hackers

https://t.co/o7TSZwckAr

To improve your chances of success:

- Start small.
- Obsessively help others.
- If an idea isn't working, quit.
- If your journey isn't working, persist.
- Study your mistakes. Don't repeat them.
- Be accountable to someone.

Your destination exists. Keep going until you arrive.

To start a business you love:

1. Identify a group of people who bring you joy.
2. Learn what they pay for, and make them your customers.
3. Hire others like you who love the same people.
4. Set sane habits. Be patient. Enjoy the journey.

Who you're with > what you're doing.

To start a business that's lucrative:

1. Find people motivated to make money.
2. Relentlessly help them make more, faster, easier.
3. Ensure their gains are attributable to you.
4. Broadcast their success stories.
5. Charge more than you'd think.

To get rich, make others rich.
@imdoru The best hack is to schedule something you dread doing, then procrastinate by doing other things you need to get done but dread a little bit less.
@jstnchu Chores + podcasts are the holy grail. Also, long walks outside.

Here's the set of coding tasks I can do while listening to audio:

• large, mindless refactors

• building straightforward CRUD features in a codebase I know well

• designing in HTML/CSS, and doing that thing where you constantly flip between your browser and your CSS
@vanschneider @IndieHackers What are your most controversial opinions on the most controversial topics of the day?

I've found there's a limited set of coding tasks I can do while simultaneously listening to an audiobook or podcast, and have full retention.

This research might shed some light onto why.

It's okay to suck. Just start.

text: @spakhm You don't think Trump massively amplified mistrust in the media, elections, etc? He's a US president with a massive platform who's been repeating "fake news" ad nauseum for years now. From what I recall, these barely even registered as talking points 4 years ago.

@tjrwriting @spakhm Even if the entire institution is wrong about something, the argument still holds. The healthcare system has made systemic mistakes time after time for centuries. But I'm not about to start seeing witchdoctors.

To dismiss an entire industry, you need a better alternative.

@spakhm Sure, people from institutions make mistakes all the time. That's worthy of specifically-targeted criticism and debate.

But it doesn't justify wholesale discarding all trust in the *entire* institution, and then replacing it with even more fallible sources of information.
These podcast pitch emails go from 100 to 0 real fast nowadays 😂 https://t.co/GsblP8NsSn

@swamy_g The president is the driving force behind tens (maybe hundreds) of millions of people believing that elections are shams, epidemiologists are idiots, etc. But I often criticize the media for various things myself and don't disagree with you.
@williamb03xx Every institution is fallible. That doesn't justify abandoning them wholesale for much worse alternatives.

Half of America now distrusts their peers involved in the media, science, or expertise of any kind.

Fact checking, peer review, and accountability are out.

Instead, rumor, conspiracy theory, and the words of politicians reign supreme.

No president has ever done this much harm.

text:
Check out the rest of my convo with @alex to catch the rest!

We get into the nitty gritty to talk about metrics, social media, showing up on Google search, hiring and managing journalists, differentiating from the competition, and more.

https://t.co/OV3BPMJMoA

🏆 Quality matters. People want to read good writing.

You'll get better with practice, so write a lot. You can also hire pro journalists for cheap, and copywriters to catch errors that would turn readers off.

"No good piece of writing you've read was ever done by one person."

context_annotations: [{'domain': {'id': '46', 'name': 'Brand Category', 'description': 'Categories within Brand Verticals that narrow down the scope of Brands'}, 'entity': {'id': '781974596752842752', 'name': 'Services'}}, {'domain': {'id': '47', 'name': 'Brand', 'description': 'Brands and Companies'}, 'entity': {'id': '10045225402', 'name': 'Twitter'}}]
text:
🥗 Mix it up. There's no single formula that readers won't get bored of.

Write about a variety of topics, in a variety of formats, and promote through a variety of channels.

Use the quick feedback loops you get from places like Twitter to iterate and double down on what works.

context_annotations: [{'domain': {'id': '46', 'name': 'Brand Category', 'description': 'Categories within Brand Verticals that narrow down the scope of Brands'}, 'entity': {'id': '781974596752842752', 'name': 'Services'}}, {'domain': {'id': '47', 'name': 'Brand', 'description': 'Brands and Companies'}, 'entity': {'id': '10045225402', 'name': 'Twitter'}}]
text:
🎓 Read everything. Learn constantly. Journalists live on Twitter for a reason.

"I'm always trying to talk to people, to listen, to ask probing questions to learn more, so I have more to write about. When news breaks, I have a lot in the back of my head that I can bring up."

🗞 Freshness matters. Use news hooks. People read and share stories about what's happening in the present.

Even if you just want to make a broader point, "hang that on top of something that's happening that people are searching for, looking for, that they care about now."

📖 Don't just deliver facts. Instead, tell stories *around* the facts.

"Build context and walk people through why something matters."

Not only do stories help connect the dots for readers, but they're more entertaining, easier to read through, and more likely to be shared.

👊 Don't quit. It takes a long time to build trust and get an audience going.

The entire first year of Crunchbase News was slow. "It was grind."

@alex and crew wrote daily for a "much smaller audience" than anticipated before reaching substantial numbers.

But they didn't quit.

Rule #1 for building a media company: 

📈 Be prolific. Consistency is table stakes.

"Everyone knows this is true, but the reason why no one does it is because it's hard."

@alex had published 7 articles in the 24 hours before I spoke with him.

Producing evergreen content is overrated. Consuming evergreen content is underrated.

text:
I don't know if there's solution to the overall predicament.

But if you want to be a happier, more pleasant person, and have a better experience reading things on Twitter (and elsewhere online), you can start by reminding yourself to read things as charitably as possible.

context_annotations: [{'domain': {'id': '46', 'name': 'Brand Category', 'description': 'Categories within Brand Verticals that narrow down the scope of Brands'}, 'entity': {'id': '781974596752842752', 'name': 'Services'}}, {'domain': {'id': '47', 'name': 'Brand', 'description': 'Brands and Companies'}, 'entity': {'id': '10045225402', 'name': 'Twitter'}}]
text:
Twitter makes it easier to be uncharitable:

• Retweets/quotes take statements out of context.

• People have 1000s of followers. Tweets may be useful or interesting for some subset, but confusing or mundane to others.

• Tweets are bite-sized. Little room for explanation.

When all you see are words and not facial expressions, tone, gestures, etc., suddenly there's more ambiguity and numerous interpretations.

(Amusingly, emojis help with this.)

But if you don't like the speaker, you're very likely to assume the least charitable interpretation.

text:
The costs are probably worth the benefits? Remote work, digital nomadism, etc. are great. Especially during this pandemic, remote work is quite literally a lifesaver.

But I love seeing things that minimize the costs. Being able to go to meetups when traveling, for example.

The feedback loop is: better communication and transportation technology ▶️ more connection between people ▶️ justifies and enables more isolated lifestyles ▶️ creates need for even better tech to stay connected ▶️ repeat.
As an individual, I'm excited about technologies that help connect me to people when we're apart. On a societal level, I worry about how all of this leads to increasingly isolated living.

Do fewer things, but do them better.

Yes, you need multiple factors to succeed, but they don't all provide equal leverage. Imagine:

(100,000 × problem) × (10,000 × distribution) × (1,000 × solution) × etc = success

Even that's coarse. "Problem" has its own equation with market size, pricing, competition…

The entrepreneurs who make more money with the same effort as others usually do so because they get the biggest thing right: picking the right problem to solve.

Everything else is secondary.

When you pick a problem people are willing to pay a lot to solve…

Selling is easier, bc customers understand the problem and care more about it.

Profitability comes faster, bc you need fewer customers.

Growth is easier, bc you can afford to spend more per customer.

Most successful companies, both VC-funded and bootstrapped, focus on obvious problems:

Helping businesses grow, or hire, or accept payments. Educating people, or providing food, lodging, or transportation. Basics.

Boring problems, innovative solutions. Not the other way around.

High-value problems are usually easy to spot: just look at what people and businesses are already spending lots of time and money on.

This is counterintuitive. Many founders try to solve unsolved problems. 99.99% of unsolved problems are unsolved bc nobody cares enough to pay.

Value is primarily determined by the problem you're solving, not by your solution to that problem.

You can spend a year crafting the world's best pencil. Maybe it sells for $50.

Or spend a week helping a company hire an engineer, in the scrappiest way possible, and make $5k.

There's a common misconception about where high prices come from: "I'm just one person. Nobody will pay a lot for something I built myself." 

Except customers don't pay for (or even know about) the work you put in. They pay for the value they get.

All else being equal, charging higher prices means making more money.

Would you rather sell 100 subscriptions that make you $250/month each or $5/month each? The answer is obvious.

Yet for various (usually bad) reasons, many indie hackers choose path #2.

My answer is simple: The entrepreneurs earning more are solving problems that are more valuable.

Put even more simply: They're selling things that have a higher price.

Why do some entrepreneurs earn more than others?

https://t.co/EytqPRZ7vr

The information you need is out there. The problems you encounter are solvable. The lifestyle you want is attainable.

The only questions are whether or not you believe that, and what you're going to do about it.

I've never met anyone more willing to ask for help than @petecodes (and ofc @lynnetye).

It's no accident they've overcome major obstacles to build successful businesses on their first few tries.

It takes an abundance of optimism to trust in others and seek out answers.

text:
😭 Scarcity: "Starting a business is impossible. There's so much I don't know. I can't do it."

🤗 Abundance i.e. @petecodes: "There's so much help! I'll learn along the way, listen to every @IndieHackers ep, ask my heroes @levelsio and @lynnetye for tips, and apply all of it."

😤 Scarcity: "It's so hard to make money. I need to resort to every sleazy coercive tactic I hear of to guilt and annoy people into buying."

😎 Abundance: "I want all of my interactions to be enjoyable. If someone says no, no big deal. There will be plenty of other customers."

😬 Scarcity: "Good ideas are rare. I'll settle for this one, even though it's boring/unethical/soul crushing, because there's no way I'll find another."

🥳 Abundance: "There are practically infinite great ideas! I'll only examine those that are both meaningful and enjoyable."
You don't need to choose between starting something to help others or starting something to help yourself. You can do both. You SHOULD do both.

text:
What's an abundance mindset look like? Ask @petecodes.

Six months ago he worked for minimum wage under horrible conditions.

Today he works for himself, runs an online biz he loves (@noCSdegree), and helps others realize their dreams. 

He didn't settle.

https://t.co/Sz3Cs0h1Tg

An abundance mindset means optimism.

You keep going when you hit obstacles. You believe there's plenty of opportunity, and you're proactive about finding it. You're picky, so you don't settle for less than you deserve.

Most successful founders I meet have an abundance mindset.

Scarcity mindset is the belief that there's not enough to go around.

It leads to tunnel vision. You become obsessed with preserving what you have, so you fail to see new opportunities right in front of you.

As a founder, what you want is the exact OPPOSITE perspective.

Another day, another indie hacker gets to ramen profitability! 🎉

https://t.co/HqaONfuTmA https://t.co/mPiBxVk4uF
@petecodes Your version motivated me to look up the real quote!
"The person who believes they can do it—and the person who believes they cannot—are both right."

People say you need to be miserable to be successful. It gives meaning to their own choices and lifestyle. I've been there and done+said the same things.

But I've also met dozens of founders like @dragilev who are crushing it in just 10 or 20 hours a week.

There will always be more good ideas than you have time for. Focusing requires the discipline to say no to most of them anyway.

text:
Most of the stress and deadlines you experience as a founder are self-imposed, from the moment you choose an idea.

Answering to investors, providing mission-critical software, prioritizing customer support as a selling point, and so on — these are all choices. Choose wisely.

"Nobody needs that much time to do the work they do. People spend a ton of time procrastinating."

Set time constraints and you'll work more efficiently.

@dragilev and his wife Corey work on their business from 9am-2pm, M-F, then shut their laptops.

"I know at 2pm, it's over."

"I'm not going to trade this time in my life, my 30s, for some big exit in 10 years. This is a conscious decision. I want to remember this decade primarily as a time with my family, friends, and kid. I made a conscious effort to build the business around that." —@dragilev

.@dragilev looked into the lives of his heroes and didn't like what he found.

"Horrible family lives, just horrible personal relationships… but they're the most successful people in the business world."

So he deliberately decided his goal was to spend more time with family.

How do you build a business that works for you instead of the other way around?

"You need to know what your purpose in life is."

Before you start a company, ask yourself what kind of life you want to live. That's step 1. If you don't have a vision, work will decide it for you.

I spoke with @dragilev on the @IndieHackers podcast.

He bootstrapped his business JustReachOut to $30,000/month working just 25 hours a week.

"I've built a very comfortable life for myself… I could probably work less and keep up this lifestyle."

https://t.co/3qeY35sDQn

In @arvidkahl's words, "FeedbackPanda has been an overnight success many, many years in the making.

"I'd listen to all the podcasts I could and I was reading lots of books. If you just take in enough of the correct kind of info, it sticks, and it changes your way of thinking."

In just two years, @arvidkahl and @SimpsonDaniK started a business, bootstrapped it to $55k/mo, and sold it for a life-changing sum, all without raising any money or hiring a single employee.

Arvid came on the @IndieHackers podcast to share exactly how:

https://t.co/Ktr84Buu6i

What's the alternative to waiting for your intuition to develop?

Reading, learning, and absorbing as much as you can.

Whatever you're doing, ppl have done it before, made dozens of mistakes, and shared what they know.

And heading into 2020, it's all just a few keystrokes away.

People are often told by their role models to trust their intuition.

But not everybody's intuition is the same.

You need to hone your intuition through years of experience and learning before it's worth anything at all. If you're new to something, intuition isn't enough.

Today @Ghost does millions in revenue and supports millions of indie journalists and writers, but it didn't start that way.

I had @JohnONolan back on the @IndieHackers podcast to share how he got here and how others can do the same.

https://t.co/2WCQgarl7q

Even if your mission is a "selfish" one — to have more freedom, to make more money, to control your time and creativity — that's a perfectly fine place to start.

Hit that goal, then move on to the next one. Let your ambition grow over time instead of trying to start at the end.

Someone posted today about the immense pressure they feel to do something meaningful.

The best thing you can do is start small, then proceed incrementally. Just look one step ahead.

As the cliche goes, you walk 1000 miles by taking one step at a time.

https://t.co/3A0OhKfDVu

Quality journalism has been dying a slow death for decades, and John wanted to change that.

But instead of tackling the biggest, sexiest challenges upfront, he started simple: by building better blogging software.

Most big things have humble beginnings.

Most indie hackers never raise money. But John went a step further and permanently locked himself in from day 1.

Ghost is a nonprofit, meaning he can never sell the business or raise money. He's turned down $10M checks from investors.

His only path forward is his mission. https://t.co/49qCz6Q6Fc

Which is more interesting to you when listening to the @IndieHackers podcast:

The similar themes, strategies, habits, and traits that tie successful founders together?

Or the differences and idiosyncrasies that make each founder and their journey unique?

Since then, Robert's learned to code, created dozens of products (and even sold one), and bootstrapped @helperbird_ into a profitable business that helps tens of thousands of ppl with learning disabilities. 

His #1 takeaway? "You should never give up."

https://t.co/PEWojTC3FM

Unfortunately, the opposite can also happen. There's a negative feedback loop that's easy to fall into when you're pessimistic or lack self confidence: "I haven't done much in the past, so I'll probably fail now, so I might as well not even try."

It's a tough cycle to escape.

If you believe you can do something great, you're more likely to try. The more often you try, the more often you'll succeed. And a history of past successes boosts your confidence and ambition, so you try more things, and the cycle repeats.

Believe 👉 try 👉 succeed 👉 repeat.

I'm a big believer in optimism as a self-fulfilling prophecy: If you believe you can do something, you're much more likely to accomplish it.

This doesn't require any magical woo-woo stuff. It's a simple positive feedback loop.

I pay $30/week for someone to teach me chess for 60 minutes. He never wants to stop, so we usually go for 90.

I have no particular goals with this. I might drop it in another few months. But it's great  to "hang out" with an expert who's passionate and pushes me past my limits.
@sarahhum Thanks for helping create an awesome episode!

@get_eo @vanschneider @IndieHackers Nope. I used to track my time religiously a few years back, but not anymore. It's just that it's happened enough times I recognize the pattern where I simultaneously feel bad about not tweeting enough *and* feel good about shipping quickly. Could be a coincidence but doubtful.

@sarahhum The #1 reason is some version of, "I don't have any ideas" or "my ideas aren't good enough."

The top remedy for that is rarely coming up with the perfect idea. More often, it's realizing that a business idea doesn't need to be 100% unique to be good.

@sarahhum I've been surveying IHers, and the #2 reason people don't start a business is believing they don't have the skills/experience.

What's gets them over the hump? Surprisingly, it's not picking up more skills. Rather, it's realizing they'll never be "ready," but diving in anyway.

text: @ProductHunt @Abadesi Finally, don't spend all morning writing a Twitter thread with no end in sight. 🤗

@danielvlopes 👍 The Goldilocks Principle of "just the right amount" certainly applies here.

Also, iterating on a product doesn't require the accumulation of code or features. Continually adding features to a product that customers don't want is a failure mode regardless of code quality.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi And starting small isn't even a sacrifice! It's necessary, even if your true desire is to reach some bigger ultimate goal.

You're going to have to work your way there, accruing advantages and using them to get to the next level. Nobody jumps straight to the top of a staircase.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't start too big.

Given the same time frame, you can either do a great job on something simple, or a mediocre job on something expansive. I guarantee it'll be more rewarding for both you and your customers if you choose the former.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't build in silence. I'm often guilty of this one. Show off what you're up to!

People love to see your thought process, peak behind the scenes, subscribe, and give you feedback and encouragement. Building in public is one of the best ways to increase your luck surface area.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi You can and probably should be growing and learning from your customers before you launch. And your launch itself should serve some purpose in helping you continue to grow.

For some businesses a splashy launch is invaluable, but for many I doubt it's even useful as a concept.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't put launch day on such a pedestal.

"Launching" has become such an established concept that it blinds founders to all the other days that exist before and after launching. Those days are 99.9% of your company's existence. Launch is just one day of growth out of many.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi In fact, there are many "diseconomies of scale" -- inferior strategies that bigger companies HAVE to adopt that they would frankly prefer not to. It'd be a tragedy to blindly copy these as an early-stage founder and throw away what makes you uniquely nimble and effective.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi More broadly, don't copy founders or companies who are way further ahead than you are. If you're going to copy them, copy what they did in the early days, not what they're doing now.

Many of the strategies that work at scale are often deadly to early-stage companies.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't try to be too clever when finding your first users.

Going from 1M to 2M users requires a bulletproof strategy, considerable knowledge, and a healthy dose of luck. Going from 1 to 2 users requires… a conversation.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't wait to start learning from your customers.

Talk to customers about what you're doing from day #1. Figure out where they hang online and learn from their conversations. Try to get a strong sense of what they'll think about your product before you waste months building it.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi There are many thousands of businesses that solve more-or-less the same old problems, but in unique ways, or for a unique segment of customers, etc. You're probably better off picking a very straightforward problem to solve, and then getting innovative with your solution.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't equate being a founder with being an inventor. It's an analogy that can easily go too far.

You'll end up overvaluing and over-protecting your pet ideas. Or worse, you'll never come up with an idea at all, because you'll assume that it needs to be something completely new.

@ProductHunt @Abadesi (This applies to any and all advice in life, btw, not just advice for how to start and run a company. It's almost never a good time to turn off your brain and blindly follow what others are saying.)

@ProductHunt @Abadesi Don't blindly follow advice without considering the context in which the advice was given (from who, to who, when, for what) and adapting it to fit your personal situation.

E.g. advice that works for a high-growth VC-funded startup might be disastrous to your indie business.

@bjc290 Lots of talking to users + talking to other founders + experimenting with things and analyzing the results. But I wouldn't say I've ever been "sure."

It's impossible to be 10x smarter than someone, but it's possible to be 100,000,000,000x richer.

As a founder, it's tough to execute 100x or even 10x better, but it's quite possible to have an idea that's 100,000x better.

There's a lot of leverage in working on the right thing.
@NikhilAgrawal44 @IndieHackers Not at the moment. Worried it would mean lots of people who share their numbers would stop sharing.

The temptation for new founders is to pick creative problems that nobody is solving.

But you're probably better off if you pick boring or obvious problems, and then get creative with your solution.

More recently:

"I can't stick to boring routines. I need variety." It turns out I'm really loving my new morning routine.

"I hate exercise and only do it out of necessity." Actually, if I keep my workouts short and I track my progress, I love trying to beat yesterday's numbers.

A bad one from high school: "I'm super lazy, but I can still do well on things."

A good replacement after @MIT kicked my ass: "My secret weapon is that I'm an absurdly hard worker."

A big one for me used to be, "I'm an introvert, so I will tire out quickly in social situations."

Eventually I realized it was an exaggeration and I got over myself, but that was the most tiring year of my life. Confirmation bias is rough. 😅

When you accept negative or self-limiting narratives about yourself, they become self-fulfilling. You reprogram yourself to lock them in. Luckily, the same is true of positive beliefs!

text:
@copyhackers @rdutel @remotiveio @aphahn @gedaly Something @copyhackers asks everyone: "How do users get to this page? What do they know?"

Tailor your landing pages 👌

Tough with just a homepage:

"We don't ever know what traffic is coming to a homepage. People are coming from all over the place with lots of different ideas."

@copyhackers @rdutel @remotiveio @aphahn Joanna to indie hacker @gedaly, who's working on a training program:

"No one's excited about learning. They're more excited about the *outcome* of learning… When you're writing, don't think about your training itself. Think about getting them to the outcome that they want."

text:
@tribemagazine It's true that tech = strongest media distribution channel = lots of control.

But the media itself remains staunchly anti-tech, incl media distributed via tech-owned channels. Almost every story on tech I encounter via Facebook/Google/Twitter/my phone is critical or skeptical.

On the flip side, tech largely controls *access* to the media, a power which is (rightfully) terrifying to media organizations.

Ironically, if that power were used as ruthlessly as it could be, the backlash would be worse for tech than anything the media could do on its own.
One interesting thing about the ongoing war between the media and tech is that the media largely controls the narrative, by virtue of being… the media.

text:
@vitabenes Don't disagree, but intuition is built from a lifetime of experience and analysis.

I'd guess Jeff Bezos' intuition about what to do with Amazon is a lot better than anyone else's, just like a fireman's intuition about what to do in a burning house will be better than ours.

@coachcalledlife Good question. The answer is that you'll never be able to do a *perfect* job… but you're still best served by thinking about costs vs benefits, even if they're just guesses and estimates.
The one exception to this is in time-sensitive situations, where you don't have much time to analyze, and you're likely to neglect some costs or benefits. Then your intuition *MAY* be a better tool.

PSA: All decisions should come down to a cost-benefit analysis. There is no better tool for decision-making.

If you're asking, "Should I do X?" then you should be weighing the costs vs benefits, while being careful to ignore sunk costs, take into account opportunity costs, etc.

Underrated: Sitting down and making sincere attempts to predict your future.

@avclark What I mean is — what keeps you going through the patches where you don't love the doing? If you can find a job where the day-to-day tasks are always pleasant then that's great, nothing else is needed. But I don't think that describes any founder's job for very long.
@ryanckulp I do wonder how many startups would exist if there was a law against >$1M exits.
@uibreakfast Definitely the best possible position to be in 👌

@grepmeded @ossia @freeCodeCamp That's awesome to hear, don't think anyone else has told me they've gone through it twice! Any suggestions for guests, for questions you'd like me to ask more often, etc?

@vanschneider Also, I'd describe you as someone who prioritizes what's fun and avoids/quits things that aren't, which is one reason you're so prolific. 🤗 It's also a totally different path to success. That variety of experiences really pays off.

@nthnclrk Of course none of this applies if your job rarely gets hard and is almost always enjoyable. Obsession with the destination and the bigger mission is only a boon when the day-to-day gets tough, which I think will be the case for every founder at some point.

text: @nthnclrk Elon is a good example. Has many tough days, but keeps going bc of his passion for the end goal, whereas I've had friends quit SpaceX bc they didn't like their manager. Different motivations. Who stays when things are tough? I'd guess the ppl passionate about the destination.

@vanschneider For me it's different as a maker vs founder. Very short feedback loop bw doing design/code work and enjoying the results. I get 50 wins per day and it's always fun.

As a founder I have bigger goals that I'll march toward even when it's not fun. Wouldn't keep going without those.
@nthnclrk In those cases the process, because the going never gets tough. The job is the same enjoyable thing every day. But if things get tough and no longer enjoyable, who stays?
@nthnclrk It's easier to remain, say, a programmer without a passion for some ultimate goal. But how far will you go as a founder if your primary motivation is performing only tasks you enjoy? 🤔
@nthnclrk I'd guess that's more true in domains where the day-to-day work is consistently pleasant, less true in domains where it changes often and hard times and drudgery are inevitable.
There's a subtle difference between loving what you do, and loving the *results* of what you do. The latter is the kind of passion that keeps you going when things get tough.

text:
Just backed @nathanbarry's Kickstarter: https://t.co/aegaBoNrPS

It's a coffee table book featuring the stories of online makers and creators, such a great idea! 🙏

If I had to describe the mindset, it's something like, "My company is on a pre-ordained path to being the greatest, and I'm currently acting out page 2 of the 50-page script that will inevitably be written about this."

(I'm not saying this to hate btw. Confidence is useful.)

I wonder where the former mindset comes from. 🤔

From expectations set by investors? External validation provided investors? The examples set by their role models and peers? The confidence required to fundraise?

Or maybe different personalities simply pick different paths.

Many (but not all) "high-growth" startup founders I talk to project an image of being rich, famous, and successful, regardless of how early their startup is. Whereas the indie hackers I meet tend to live in the present and are more realistic about the challenges in front of them.
@tnorthcutt I honestly think everyone should see a (good) therapist.

Being in a relationship and being a founder — not always the easiest path to navigate. Been thinking about this a lot in recent weeks, and there are some thoughtful responses here. https://t.co/ffgKN56uND

And yes, I realize the irony that this entire point is itself somewhat contrarian. 🙈

Information spreads quickly enough that you should expect many people to already know about and be doing the "best" things. An obsession with being the first, being the only, or being contrarian is an addiction to novelty, and can cause you to miss out on obviously good things.

In a world where it's fashionable to be a contrarian and react with instant and automatic dismissal toward the things that "everyone" is doing, I think you can go a long way just giving the benefit of the doubt to large numbers of smart people.

text: @marckohlbrugge The number of people who've told me I should delete the @IndieHackers forum and use a Facebook group instead… 🤦‍♀️

Finding out how to provide value requires leaving the prescribed path they created for you (and everyone else) and doing your own exploring.

At that point, you're operating like a business with a customer, and venturing out to start your own business won't seem like such a leap.
To bridge that gap, your best bet is to identify the levers you can pull to *directly* create value for your employer, usually by making (or saving) them meaningful amounts of money.

Following a well-defined track at BigCo will always lead to a disconnect between what you contribute and what you get out of it. It's nigh impossible to accurately determine the value of an employee outside of some specific measurable tasks and roles, e.g. sales.

Ignore the size of the gap between you and the people you admire, even if it's huge. Focus instead on whether that gap is shrinking. If the gap is shrinking, then it's only a matter of time until it's gone.

The experts in most professions plateau after a while. I can vouch for it in software engineering and in startups.

This is good news for beginners. It means no matter how late you start, you can catch up. Keep learning, don't stop, don't get comfortable. 🎓

And when people give you negative feedback about your startup idea, don't get discouraged. Instead, think about it as challenges to overcome that you might not have otherwise anticipated. You want to know about as many of these hurdles as you can.
This is one reason why reading stories about other founders is so helpful. You get to "cheat" and see where they tend to get stuck vs where they breeze through without a hiccup.
So when it's a surprise to find out that it's hard to get people to buy your thing, use your thing, understand your thing, or even *find* your thing, then… 🙊

How many founders spend months thinking up a clever idea, designing shiny features, and believe it'll all be smooth sailing after that?

Most movies, TV shows, and news about startups will tell you that you're right, too.
@mubashariqbal Exactly, which sucks for people who think the next big challenge is to spend a month designing the perfect logo and slogan
One of the hard parts of startups, especially for new founders, is actually *knowing* what the hard parts are.

Reading about unique tricks and rare hacks is fun, but people have been shouting the best stuff from the rooftops for years.

"Target a niche, make a product for them."
"Obviously!"
*builds something equally mediocre for everyone, never gets customers, quits*

"Do what you love."
"I don't see how that could ever work."
*starts something uninteresting, things get hard, quits immediately*

"Talk to your users."
"Sure, right after I build these features."
*codes for 6 months, talks to no one, zero research, launch fails, quits*
My strongest belief is that counterintuitive advice is overrated. The best advice is common, straightforward, and tragically ignored. https://t.co/ZJLwxOt0N4

@mbuckbee For example, eliminates the entire class of A+ ideas that don't solve a painful problem for customers yet massively amplify their revenue
@mbuckbee I think the focus on the pain/problem zooms in on just one of many reasons why customers might want something, ignores other reasons
@mbuckbee There are also things ppl want that don't solve a problem/need. In the end, the only thing that matters is whether or not people want it
@mbuckbee There are problems that nobody cares about, "needs" they don't mind neglecting, and solutions they'll refuse to adopt. Dangerous lures…
@mbuckbee Looking at problems and needs is a sensible but rough heuristic for finding what people "want very badly." Important to know it can be wrong
@mbuckbee Seen founders fail bc they focus on solving problems and filling needs, ignore whether ppl actively *want* their solution
@mbuckbee I think it comes off that way b/c the differences in word choice are so subtle, but they lead to substantively different ways to run a biz
@rsobers @mijustin Then people are using those products because they *want* those sharp, tiny pains solved.

text: @TrevMcKendrick Yeah, spending a couple hours on Twitter this morning has been "work" for me, arguably
@ajlkn @andreasklinger @levelsio Partly why I'm not convinced that the research on how long hours affect avg employees also applies perfectly to founders, makers, etc
@equartey @amyhoy Where we're probably talking past each other is I interpreted her analogy "love of alcohol [is toxic]" as saying that love of work is toxic
@levelsio @ajlkn Did this once, 80 hrs/wk for 2 years straight. Regret it looking back (you don't make memories in flow state), but I was happy at the time
@amyhoy Fair, I'm probably misunderstanding your point. What did you disagree with when I said overwork is often a side effect of passion for work?
@amyhoy Point being, I'm not convinced it's worth throwing away the passion itself to avoid the negative effects, if the negatives can be isolated
@amyhoy I still love working for its own sake just as much today, if not more (it's more impactful). But I'm much wiser about handling that impulse
@amyhoy B/c I had no ability to moderate, I missed out on a lot of life. Basically created zero memories for 2 years. And the startup failed anyway
@amyhoy I honestly loved what I was working on for its own sake, and was on balance fairly happy, but I look back on that time with a lot of regret
@amyhoy I once spent 2 years averaging 10+ hours/day, 7 days/week coding for my startup, and neglected personal relationships and experiences
@amyhoy Maybe this is just semantics, but I dont think the passion/love itself is toxic. It's the lack of ability/tools/understanding to moderate it
And if you aren't informed, then you're liable to make the wrong sacrifices, and decrease your quality of life AND your chances of success
If you're conscious of what you're doing, then making strategic sacrifices to help achieve your goals is a perfectly fine way to live a life
I don't think that's something to champion or to shame. Better to just be aware of the consequences and the tradeoffs you're making
Hard to do if you aren't passionate about your goals/the work itself. A side effect of that passion is often overwork & sacrificing too much
Do you have to work crazy hours to succeed? Not at all. It's sticking with it over the long term that matters most, not short-term bursts
That said, the most common reason I've come across for entrepreneurs failing (besides never starting) is losing motivation & quitting early
People often lie about how much they work, and others routinely overestimate their capacity. I've personally burned myself out many times
There's a pervasive myth (and a culture built around it) that you need 80 hour weeks to do anything significant, and it does a lot of harm
Ultimately, with very few exceptions, working a lot and missing out on sleep will take its toll on your decision-making and productivity
And rather than having a discussion in lieu of the evidence, we should instead take the research into account (https://t.co/Fi057V45dr)
At the risk of being Wrong on the Internet™, I think this is a worthwhile discussion for founders to have beyond "work more" or "work less" https://t.co/4hsUIrswx4
@surfcoderepeat @ChanningAllen Should be mostly self-policing nowadays since users can flag threads, but I'll eventually add some more automation to it
